'''Bridgette Radebe''' (n<U+00E9>e '''Motsepe''') is a [[South Africa]]n businesswoman and the older sister of South African businessman [[Patrice Motsepe]].

==Summary==
She was born on February 26, 1960.<ref name="africansuccess">[http://www.africansuccess.org/visuFiche.php?id=385&lang=en ''Bridgette Radebe''] biography at AfricanSuccess.org</ref> Radebe started out as a [[miner]] in the 1980s; managing indvidual [[mine shaft]]s and producing materials for the larger mine operations in South Africa.<ref name="bridgette">[http://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2011/05/02/africas-richest-women/ ''Bridgette Radebe''] career information at Forbes.com</ref> She started [[Mmaku Mining]]; a mining firm which explorers for and produces [[platinum]], [[gold]], and [[chrome]].<ref name="bridgette"/>

Radabe is the President of the [[South African Mining Development Association]] and her husband is South Africa's [[Minister of Justice and Constitutional Development]] [[Jeff Radebe]].<ref name="bridgette"/> She is also the member of the [[New Africa Mining Fund]] and serves on the [[Sappi Board]].<ref name="africansuccess"/><ref>[http://www.mmakaumining.co.za/about_board.htm ''Bridgette Radebe''] information at Mmakau Mining.co.za</ref> Bridgette has criticized the "[[capitalism|capitalist]] mining model" because "it takes land to exploit the materials, the exports create [[ghost town]]s, and jobs go overseas.<ref name="justpolitics">[http://www.politicsweb.co.za/politicsweb/view/politicsweb/en/page71619?oid=201752&sn=Detail&pid=71619 Critique of South Africa's capitalist model] at PoliticsWeb.co.za</ref>" When South Africa was re-created 83% of the natural resources belonged to the racial minority (white people). Today, 91% of the same resources are owned by corporate monopolies.<ref name="justpolitics"/> She suggests three solutions to solve the problem: 1) complete [[nationalization]] of all mining operations, 2) a state [[buyout]] of the mining operations of dwindling profitability in the name of black empowerment, 3) a [[co-operation]] movement between [[public sector|public]] and [[private sector]]s over the running of South Africa's mines.<ref name="justpolitics"/>

Radabe received an "International Businessperson of the Year Award" on May 2008 by the [[Global Foundation for Demcracy]].<ref name="africansuccess"/> This award recognizes businesspeople who have made the different in a world of changing political and environmental landscapes.<ref name="africansuccess"/> Originally barred by legislation to start her own enterprise, Bridgette is a heroic woman who has defied racial segregation to acquiring a mining license and accomplish her goals.<ref name="beyondsport">[http://www.beyondsport.org/the-summit/speaker/speaker/profile.php?Id=7&ProfileId=91 ''Bridgette Radebe''] at BeyondSport.org</ref> Through her tenure as the President of the [[Junior Mining Chamber]], Radebe has alleviated poverty and restored the dignity of the [[native African]] people.<ref name="beyondsport"/> Her model is now being used in various mining chambers all across Africa.<ref name="beyondsport"/> On July 1-2, 2011, Radebe assisted the wedding of [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco|Prince Albert II of Monaco]] and the former [[Charlene, Princess of Monaco|Charlene Wittstock]].<ref name="africansuccess"/>

